review_blob: Pours a gorgeous orange with a thick, frothy head. Smell is full of malt, with great citrus fruits lingering. Lots of lemon, grapefruit, pine and simple hop. First sip is sweet on the tongue, syrupy in feel. Very sweet but it really dries out. Extreme hop with a resinous coating. There is a surprising lack of booze in the big imperial, but I really enjoy that it is so very drinkable! This is a tasty summer treat for all the hop heads out there. Enjoy

Pours like syrup with a tight, tan head. Smell is chocolate with minor notes of burnt sugar and toffee. In first sip, it is very light in booze with an extremely sweet tongue feel. Its dry and bubbly with taste of coffee, chocolate, brown sugar. It is a deep, sugary brew with a lot of potential. Got one in the cellar to see what orbs complexities unfold!
Very predictable double. Decent fruit noise with a hop palate. It had a sweet flavor and dry finish. There was citrus fruits with s but if a resin mouthfeel.

Its a beautiful pour, with dark amber color and thick beige head that stays with the brew. Nose is resinous and First sip is surprisingly low key in alcohol. This is a 2014 bottle. Sweet, malty start with a bright hop finish. Its not as clean on the palate, which I enjoy. After a few sips, it is almost the same affect as chewing on a hop flower. Those flavors linger! Great strong beer. For the alcohol, it is easy to drink. Plan so age a second bottle to test against next couple years.

Caramel and toffee nose with a mystery fruit lingering in the back. I love the intrigue of the flavor! Raisin, floral, resin, with lots of malt finish. This is a great fall beer. I plan to age one for this fall and one for next. Compare the changes in flavor

Nose of coffee and a tinge of chocolate. Taste is rather one dimential. A young bottle has a bit of bit and a tiny bit of stale coffee. I think with age, the beer would settle the alcohol and and maybe bring out something dynamic.
Intense coffee, chocolate and tobacco nose. First sip is dry and yields intense, dark coffee. Dry chocolate finish. Really really tasty brew. Intensely stout. This is a near perfect brew.

Gorgeous black pour with a beige. Woody, yet sweet smell. Strong cherry and grape flavors. Super tart with a dry lingering finish. Intriguingly tangy and strangely forgiving for the heavy alcohol. No strong boozy flavor or burning to note. Just one uniquely out there imperial stout.

Pours a hazy, straw color with minimal head. Nose is fruit and grass. Very Saison with a nice fruit twist. The taste is very tart and dry with an even finish. Not overwhelming but an excellent farmhouse brew. Very unique!
Very sweet, even for a sweet stout. Has dry malt and lactose finish with an even coffee palate. Very acidic and almost floral front. Unique taste but not the best of beers.

One of my favorite smelling beers to date! Bourbon, dark chocolate, vanilla, wood, prune, Bold coffee. Pours like oil or molasses with a thick 2.5 finger, caramel head. Dry dark Chocolate on first sip with hints of Bourbon and burnt caramel. Dry, almost creamy finish. Booziness comes out as it warms. Incredible flavor depth and profiles. One could almost find any flavor of there in this beer.

Fruity aroma starts with orange and lemons and comes on strong with mango and grapefruit. Mango is by far the most unique feature to this beer. Gives it a creamy tongue feel and a balanced, sweet sipping profile. Great summery beer!

Cherry and faint wooden notes. A sweet yet boozy aroma back the bet as well. Cherry and amaretto start, while whiskey finishes the palate. A great, evenly balanced brew that offers a lot as it sits. Incredibly dynamic flavor profule.
Chopped chocolate and hefty malt nose. A hint of spice and burnt caramel. First sip is smooth and velvety. Chocolate, roasted almond. Sweet finish that lingers. A delicious beer!

I have mixed feelings on this beer. It is excellent in a few ways: body is thick and rich, flavors are fruit and malt, nose is minimal but enticing. There isnt much that makes this beer sing though. Its pretty one level. Not the most drinkable but fairly refreshing.
Fruity nose with a nice, double ipa alcohol tone. Grapefruit, oranges, lemons. Flavors of yeast and grapefruit. A minor earthy note profile as well. Incredible.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - The Calling IPA

review_blob: Unique flavor. The nose is instant fruit and hops. Oranges, grapefruit, lemons with the natural hop aroma following. Taste is a perfectly unfiltered wheat balance. Bubblegum, hops bitter with a crisp finish. On tap, pours a beautifully cloudy glass. Super unique!
Malty with a nice hop finish. Bread, flowers, biscuits. A very balanced, tangy tongue feel. On tap, pours redish yellow. Easy drinking, like any session should be.

Pours a redish orange color with thin, no lave head. Nose is very citrus fruits and grass heavy. There are hops and orange peel on second smell. Taste is dry and finishes bitter. It pulls moisture from the tongue, leaving almost a refreshing aftertaste. Grass, apricot, hops. A solid offering for sure.

Pours classic amber with a thin white head. Nose is hoppy. There is not much diversity in the nose. Possible pine in there too. 
Taste is hops and malt.. .bread and dough mostly.
A tangy finish.
Not really much of a beer to break apart. It does drink very easy and has more body than most daily drinking beers.

A diverse beer. 
Pour: thick like molasses . A rich amber color, reminds me of syrup. 
Nose: vanilla, burnt caramel, molasses, brown sugar, honeysuckle. 
Taste: a fast punching sugar rush. It starts like a fine wine, dry and sweet. Its an overwhelming at first taste. Alcohol, bourbon, vanilla, caramel, and wood barrels. As it sits on the tongue, it sweetens even more. The flavor of honeysuckle finishes the beer. 
As it warms, the alcohol flavor enrich each sip. This is a complicated bottle. 

Overall: a huge brew to break down. Most barley wines are huge in flavor and palate. This one is no different. I think the nose is where the major differences lie in barrel aging of this beer. I plan to get a few more bottles to cellar.
